    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <g type="hedera"/> <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="servile" key="Epinicus">Epinico</name></persName>
                <lb n="3"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Gaius"><expan><abbr>C</abbr><ex>aius</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Clodius">Clodius</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Hermes">Hermes</name></persName>
                <lb n="4"/><expan><abbr>b</abbr><ex>ene</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>erenti</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ecit</ex></expan>.
            </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>To the divine spirits. Gaius Clodius Hermes made this for Epinicus, well deserving. </p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>There is a heart drawing between the first two words of line 1. Epinicus may have
                    been a slave or freedman of Gaius Clodius Hermes. Gaius Clodius Hermes is also
                    mentioned in another epitaph from Rome (CIL 6. 15741), which is for him, his
                    wife, there freedmen/freedwomen, and their descendants. Second century CE, based
                    on formula.</p>
            </div>
